00:00:41.350 --> 00:00:44.210 align:middle line:90%


00:00:44.210 --> 00:00:53.350 align:middle line:84%
So the topic that we're now
on is continuous functions.

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:57.890 align:middle line:90%


00:00:57.890 --> 00:01:04.158 align:middle line:84%
And so continuous
functions, as we'll see,

00:01:04.158 --> 00:01:06.960 align:middle line:84%
is a statement about
how a function behaves

00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:13.990 align:middle line:84%
near a point in relation to
how it behaves at the point.

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:15.790 align:middle line:84%
Now, what it means
for a function

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:18.220 align:middle line:84%
to behave near a point--
that's the notion

00:01:18.220 --> 00:01:22.238 align:middle line:84%
of the limit of
the function, which

00:01:22.238 --> 00:01:23.405 align:middle line:90%
is what we'll first discuss.

00:01:23.405 --> 00:01:33.370 align:middle line:90%


00:01:33.370 --> 00:01:34.960 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:40.280 align:middle line:84%
Now, at what points are
we going to be looking at?

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:43.840 align:middle line:84%
So this is where
limits take place.

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:48.550 align:middle line:84%
And somehow, we want to look
at a function near points

00:01:48.550 --> 00:01:53.650 align:middle line:84%
where there's a set nearby
to actually look at f at.

00:01:53.650 --> 00:01:57.310 align:middle line:84%
So f is usually
defined on some set S,

00:01:57.310 --> 00:02:00.898 align:middle line:84%
and we want to look at points so
that there's a lot of S nearby.

00:02:00.898 --> 00:02:03.190 align:middle line:84%
And we kind of already dealt
with these types of points

00:02:03.190 --> 00:02:07.450 align:middle line:84%
when we encountered cluster
points in the assignment.

00:02:07.450 --> 00:02:10.639 align:middle line:84%
So this is exactly where
we start looking at limits.

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:15.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is a
definition that I'll

00:02:15.950 --> 00:02:19.030 align:middle line:90%
recall from the assignment.

00:02:19.030 --> 00:02:30.580 align:middle line:84%
Let S be a subset
of R and x and R.

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:46.510 align:middle line:84%
We say x is a cluster point of
S if, for all delta positive,

00:02:46.510 --> 00:02:51.300 align:middle line:84%
the interval x minus delta,
x plus delta intersect

00:02:51.300 --> 00:02:59.030 align:middle line:90%
S take away x is non-empty, OK?

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:02.500 align:middle line:84%
So the new
terminology-- not so new

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:04.250 align:middle line:84%
since we dealt with
it in the assignment--

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:07.310 align:middle line:90%
is that of a cluster point.

00:03:07.310 --> 00:03:09.680 align:middle line:84%
And another way to
say this is that--

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:11.420 align:middle line:84%
so an equivalent
way of stating this

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:16.850 align:middle line:84%
is that, for all delta positive,
there exists, let's say,

00:03:16.850 --> 00:03:26.400 align:middle line:84%
a y in S such that 0 is
bigger than x minus y

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:31.150 align:middle line:90%
is less than delta, OK?

00:03:31.150 --> 00:03:37.870 align:middle line:84%
So what this means is that,
as far as the picture goes,

00:03:37.870 --> 00:03:40.270 align:middle line:84%
x is a cluster point
if, when I ever

00:03:40.270 --> 00:03:42.850 align:middle line:84%
take any small
interval about it,

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:51.970 align:middle line:84%
I can find some S in there
other than possibly x.

00:03:51.970 --> 00:03:54.730 align:middle line:84%
And this should be able to
be done for every interval.

00:03:54.730 --> 00:04:03.380 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a look
at some examples.

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:12.250 align:middle line:84%
Let's say we take S to be
1/n in a natural number, OK?

00:04:12.250 --> 00:04:15.000 align:middle line:90%


00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:25.300 align:middle line:84%
And so since now I actually
have people in front of me,

00:04:25.300 --> 00:04:27.100 align:middle line:90%
I can actually ask questions.

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:37.940 align:middle line:90%


00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:42.050 align:middle line:84%
So whoever first says
it, what would be

00:04:42.050 --> 00:04:44.103 align:middle line:90%
a cluster point of this set S?

00:04:44.103 --> 00:04:46.881 align:middle line:90%


00:04:46.881 --> 00:04:49.280 align:middle line:84%
So what would be a point
in the real numbers

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:51.340 align:middle line:84%
So that there's a
lot of S near it?

00:04:51.340 --> 00:04:55.330 align:middle line:90%


00:04:55.330 --> 00:04:57.580 align:middle line:84%
Feel free to blurt it
out if it comes to you.

00:04:57.580 --> 00:05:06.340 align:middle line:90%


00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.770 align:middle line:90%
Why don't you just take a guess?

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:09.270 align:middle line:90%
1?

00:05:09.270 --> 00:05:13.710 align:middle line:90%
So that's one possibility.

00:05:13.710 --> 00:05:20.320 align:middle line:84%
So there has to be a lot of
S near this proposed cluster

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:21.160 align:middle line:90%
point.

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:23.090 align:middle line:84%
So let me mark out the
points that we have.

00:05:23.090 --> 00:05:27.040 align:middle line:84%
There's a-- I'll
put 0, and then 1/2

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:34.670 align:middle line:84%
is there, and then 1/3, 1/4,
1/5, 1/6, so on, and so on.

00:05:34.670 --> 00:05:37.470 align:middle line:90%
And so I see a guess of 0.

00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:40.860 align:middle line:90%
So that's a good guess as well.

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:43.710 align:middle line:84%
So why would 1 maybe
not be a cluster point?

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:49.190 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's because if I draw
a little interval around 1,

00:05:49.190 --> 00:05:52.460 align:middle line:84%
then there's only one
point in S in here,

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:55.820 align:middle line:84%
and it's the proposed
cluster point, 1, OK?

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:57.770 align:middle line:84%
So remember, what we
should be able to do

00:05:57.770 --> 00:06:02.320 align:middle line:84%
is find in every small
interval [? sum ?] of S

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:05.390 align:middle line:84%
in the interval that's not
equal to the point, OK?

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:08.168 align:middle line:84%
And we can't do that
for the point 1.

00:06:08.168 --> 00:06:13.430 align:middle line:84%
But for 0, if we draw
any interval around 0,

00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:19.590 align:middle line:84%
there's plenty of S in the
interval not equal to 0, OK?

00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:31.220 align:middle line:84%
So here, 0 is a cluster
point of S. And let's

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:33.170 align:middle line:90%
give a quick proof of this.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:36.050 align:middle line:90%


00:06:36.050 --> 00:06:41.350 align:middle line:84%
So we have to verify for every
delta positive this interval, 0

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:45.040 align:middle line:84%
minus delta, 0 plus delta
intersect S take away 0

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:46.030 align:middle line:90%
is non-empty.

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:56.420 align:middle line:84%
So the delta would be positive,
and now here's the picture.

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:58.040 align:middle line:90%
Here's 0.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:02.540 align:middle line:90%
Here's delta, minus delta.

00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:04.640 align:middle line:84%
We have to show that
there's some S in here.

00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:07.690 align:middle line:84%
So we simply choose
natural number n

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:11.200 align:middle line:84%
large enough so
that 1/n is there,

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:12.940 align:middle line:84%
and we can always
do this because

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:16.602 align:middle line:84%
of the Archimedean property
of the real numbers, right?

00:07:16.602 --> 00:07:19.770 align:middle line:90%


00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:23.860 align:middle line:90%
So let delta be positive.

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:30.930 align:middle line:84%
Choose natural number n so
that 1/n is less than delta,

00:07:30.930 --> 00:07:32.700 align:middle line:84%
and it's certainly
bigger than 0.

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:35.130 align:middle line:90%
So then n is a natural number.

00:07:35.130 --> 00:07:37.910 align:middle line:90%


00:07:37.910 --> 00:07:46.330 align:middle line:84%
Then 1/n is in x minus
delta, x plus delta intersect

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:48.640 align:middle line:90%
S take away 0.

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:57.770 align:middle line:84%
So this should
have been 0, which

00:07:57.770 --> 00:08:07.220 align:middle line:84%
implies this set is non-empty
because it has something in it,

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:09.806 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:08:09.806 --> 00:08:12.220 align:middle line:90%
All right, was that example OK?

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:14.230 align:middle line:90%
Did you all get that all right?

00:08:14.230 --> 00:08:17.670 align:middle line:90%


00:08:17.670 --> 00:08:21.825 align:middle line:84%
OK, so feel free to ask
questions as they come up.

00:08:21.825 --> 00:08:28.060 align:middle line:90%


00:08:28.060 --> 00:08:29.500 align:middle line:90%
So let's do another example.

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:34.320 align:middle line:84%
This one, I will not
give a full proof of,

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:38.409 align:middle line:84%
but we'll just kind of
talk our way through it.

00:08:38.409 --> 00:08:40.975 align:middle line:84%
Let's say S is now the
open interval 0, 1.

00:08:40.975 --> 00:08:52.010 align:middle line:90%


00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:57.615 align:middle line:84%
What is the set of cluster
points of 0, 1 equal to?

00:08:57.615 --> 00:09:01.730 align:middle line:90%


00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:06.060 align:middle line:84%
So what would be a reasonable
guess or any guess?

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:14.210 align:middle line:90%


