certainly a cluster point.

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:49.310 align:middle line:90%
What about the point 1?

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:54.530 align:middle line:90%


00:09:54.530 --> 00:09:56.120 align:middle line:84%
Is that a cluster
point of this set?

00:09:56.120 --> 00:10:11.810 align:middle line:90%


00:10:11.810 --> 00:10:16.100 align:middle line:84%
That's a good observation that,
yeah, it's a sup of the set.

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:38.280 align:middle line:84%
So for every-- right, so
for every delta positive,

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:40.740 align:middle line:84%
if I draw a little
interval around 1,

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:43.590 align:middle line:84%
there's going to be
a number less than 1

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:47.670 align:middle line:84%
that's bigger than 1
minus delta, right?

00:10:47.670 --> 00:10:51.720 align:middle line:84%
The set of cluster points
of the open interval 0, 1

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:54.092 align:middle line:90%
is the closed interval 0, 1.

00:10:54.092 --> 00:10:54.592 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:10:54.592 --> 00:10:57.540 align:middle line:90%


00:10:57.540 --> 00:11:03.790 align:middle line:90%
Now, let's do another example.

00:11:03.790 --> 00:11:09.255 align:middle line:84%
Let's say we look at now,
instead of rational numbers--

00:11:09.255 --> 00:11:12.160 align:middle line:90%


00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:14.340 align:middle line:84%
so you should, again,
think of cluster points

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:22.360 align:middle line:84%
as being the set of points
where there is a lot of this set

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:26.080 align:middle line:90%
nearby, OK?

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:28.705 align:middle line:84%
Now, what is the set of cluster
points of the rational numbers?

00:11:28.705 --> 00:11:37.880 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:42.750 align:middle line:84%
OK, so perhaps it will contain
the irrational numbers.

00:11:42.750 --> 00:11:45.060 align:middle line:84%
So let's think about
this for a little bit.

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:48.020 align:middle line:84%
So, for example, let's look
at square root of 2, OK?

00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:49.700 align:middle line:90%
Perfectly good rational number--

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:51.380 align:middle line:90%
I mean, irrational number.

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:57.010 align:middle line:84%
If I draw a little interval
around square root of 2,

00:11:57.010 --> 00:12:00.310 align:middle line:84%
can I find a rational
number in there

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:02.350 align:middle line:84%
that's not equal to
a square root of 2?

00:12:02.350 --> 00:12:08.110 align:middle line:90%


00:12:08.110 --> 00:12:09.640 align:middle line:84%
Right, because we
have this theorem

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:12.880 align:middle line:84%
about the density of the
rational numbers, right,

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:13.760 align:middle line:90%
that we have--

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:19.060 align:middle line:84%
so remember that this was a
theorem we proved at one point.

00:12:19.060 --> 00:12:24.460 align:middle line:84%
For all x, y real numbers
with x less than y,

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:27.820 align:middle line:84%
there exists a
rational number r such

00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:33.946 align:middle line:84%
that x is less than r
is less than y, right?

00:12:33.946 --> 00:12:36.990 align:middle line:84%
So we can always find
a rational number here,

00:12:36.990 --> 00:12:42.180 align:middle line:84%
or we could have taken another
rational number here, yeah?

00:12:42.180 --> 00:12:45.000 align:middle line:84%
So for every interval we
draw around square root of 2,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:49.350 align:middle line:84%
we can find a rational in there
not equal to square root of 2,

00:12:49.350 --> 00:12:49.860 align:middle line:90%
obviously.

00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:53.720 align:middle line:84%
But we can find a rational
in that interval, yeah?

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:56.600 align:middle line:84%
So this suggests that
the set of cluster points

00:12:56.600 --> 00:12:59.033 align:middle line:90%
contains the set of irrationals.

00:12:59.033 --> 00:13:00.200 align:middle line:90%
What about rational numbers?

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:01.940 align:middle line:90%
Are those also cluster points?

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:06.290 align:middle line:90%


00:13:06.290 --> 00:13:08.120 align:middle line:90%
Let's say I take 0.

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:11.390 align:middle line:84%
Now I look at a small
interval around 0.

00:13:11.390 --> 00:13:13.985 align:middle line:84%
Can I find a rational number
in there other than 0?

00:13:13.985 --> 00:13:19.560 align:middle line:90%


00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:21.780 align:middle line:84%
I'm not asking like,
actually give me one.

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:25.860 align:middle line:84%
I'm just saying, does there
exist a rational number

00:13:25.860 --> 00:13:29.302 align:middle line:90%
in this interval other than 0?

00:13:29.302 --> 00:13:30.080 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:31.747 align:middle line:84%
CASEY RODRIGUEZ: By
this theorem, right?

00:13:31.747 --> 00:13:34.490 align:middle line:90%


00:13:34.490 --> 00:13:38.358 align:middle line:84%
You can also use
the theorem to find

00:13:38.358 --> 00:13:40.970 align:middle line:84%
irrational in this
interval as well.

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:45.700 align:middle line:84%
So no matter if it's square root
of 2 or any irrational number,

00:13:45.700 --> 00:13:48.310 align:middle line:84%
no matter if it's
a rational number,

00:13:48.310 --> 00:13:51.200 align:middle line:90%
everything is a cluster point.

00:13:51.200 --> 00:13:56.590 align:middle line:84%
So the set of cluster points of
rational numbers is equal to R,

00:13:56.590 --> 00:13:59.047 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:59.047 --> 00:13:59.630 align:middle line:90%
Is that clear?

00:13:59.630 --> 00:14:05.550 align:middle line:90%


00:14:05.550 --> 00:14:08.290 align:middle line:84%
OK, feel free to stop me
if you have any questions.

00:14:08.290 --> 00:14:17.072 align:middle line:84%
So now let's look
at, for example,

00:14:17.072 --> 00:14:25.520 align:middle line:84%
S equal to just a
single guy, say, 0, OK?

00:14:25.520 --> 00:14:28.440 align:middle line:84%
Remember, cluster
points of a set

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:30.240 align:middle line:84%
means there's a lot
of that set nearby.

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:35.240 align:middle line:90%


00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:38.690 align:middle line:84%
Now, I claim that this
guy has no cluster

00:14:38.690 --> 00:14:45.800 align:middle line:84%
points because if you think
so intuitively why is this,

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:48.160 align:middle line:84%
this is because, for something
to be a cluster point,

00:14:48.160 --> 00:14:52.400 align:middle line:84%
it has to have a lot of
the set near it, a lot.

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:54.710 align:middle line:84%
And there's not a lot
of set to begin with.

00:14:54.710 --> 00:14:56.285 align:middle line:90%
There's just one element.

00:14:56.285 --> 00:15:00.710 align:middle line:84%
So let's see why
this is the case, OK?

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:02.450 align:middle line:84%
And this gives us
a chance to negate

00:15:02.450 --> 00:15:06.920 align:middle line:84%
the definition of cluster point,
which is always a good idea.

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:14.030 align:middle line:84%
OK, so S equals just
the singleton set, 0.

00:15:14.030 --> 00:15:16.220 align:middle line:84%
This has no cluster
points, and so the negation

00:15:16.220 --> 00:15:17.850 align:middle line:84%
of the definition
of a cluster point--

00:15:17.850 --> 00:15:32.590 align:middle line:84%
so x is not a cluster point
of S means if this is some bad

00:15:32.590 --> 00:15:33.100 align:middle line:90%
delta--

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:36.100 align:middle line:84%
remember, so the definition of
cluster point is for all delta.

00:15:36.100 --> 00:15:40.060 align:middle line:84%
So negation means there
exists one bad delta

00:15:40.060 --> 00:15:45.430 align:middle line:84%
so that x minus delta
0, x plus delta 0

00:15:45.430 --> 00:15:55.380 align:middle line:84%
intersect S take away x
equals the empty set, OK?

00:15:55.380 --> 00:15:57.570 align:middle line:84%
So the picture that
goes along with this

00:15:57.570 --> 00:16:04.850 align:middle line:84%
is that x does not
cluster point if there's

00:16:04.850 --> 00:16:08.540 align:middle line:84%
some interval and
possibly the only S there

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:12.640 align:middle line:84%
is the point x, but
nothing else, OK?

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:17.140 align:middle line:90%


00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:21.090 align:middle line:84%
All right, so let's use the
negation of this definition

00:16:21.090 --> 00:16:25.195 align:middle line:84%
to show that there are
no cluster points, OK?

00:16:25.195 --> 00:16:28.050 align:middle line:90%


00:16:28.050 --> 00:16:31.110 align:middle line:84%
And we have to deal
with two cases.

00:16:31.110 --> 00:16:50.980 align:middle line:84%
I want to show x is in R, and
x is not a cluster point of S.

00:16:50.980 --> 00:16:54.250 align:middle line:84%
And I'll just do the
case x not equal to 0.

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:59.500 align:middle line:84%
x equal to 0 is much easier, so
we'll just do x not equal to 0.

00:16:59.500 --> 00:17:05.500 align:middle line:90%


00:17:05.500 --> 00:17:07.329 align:middle line:90%
Let's prove this.

00:17:07.329 --> 00:17:09.849 align:middle line:90%
And what's the idea?

00:17:09.849 --> 00:17:11.300 align:middle line:90%
We have to be able to find--

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:13.030 align:middle line:90%
so here's 0.

00:17:13.030 --> 00:17:16.540 align:middle line:84%
This is all that S is,
is just this point, 0.

00:17:16.540 --> 00:17:19.750 align:middle line:90%
Now we have a point x.

00:17:19.750 --> 00:17:23.579 align:middle line:84%
What would be an
interval containing

00:17:23.579 --> 00:17:25.365 align:middle line:90%
x that contains none of S?

00:17:25.365 --> 00:17:35.350 align:middle line:90%


00:17:35.350 --> 00:17:39.500 align:middle line:84%
So x here is just
some nonzero number.

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:43.330 align:middle line:90%
S is what's highlighted.

00:17:43.330 --> 00:17:56.810 align:middle line:84%
The interval around x that
doesn't contain any S. So

00:17:56.810 --> 00:17:57.370 align:middle line:90%
like a x/2?

00:17:57.370 --> 00:18:00.440 align:middle line:90%


00:18:00.440 --> 00:18:07.810 align:middle line:84%
3x over 2, meaning delta equals
x/2, at least for this picture,

00:18:07.810 --> 00:18:09.970 align:middle line:90%
yeah?

00:18:09.970 --> 00:18:11.990 align:middle line:84%
OK, and that's
essentially the proof.

00:18:11.990 --> 00:18:20.410 align:middle line:84%
So choose delta 0, and
we'll simplify this further

00:18:20.410 --> 00:18:22.000 align:middle line:90%
and suppose x is positive.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.010 align:middle line:84%
For x less than 0,
you choose delta 0

00:18:24.010 --> 00:18:26.290 align:middle line:90%
to be the absolute value of x.

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:28.420 align:middle line:84%
But for this one, this
is simple enough--

00:18:28.420 --> 00:18:39.530 align:middle line:84%
choose delta 0 to be x/2 and x
minus delta 0, x plus delta 0

00:18:39.530 --> 00:18:43.260 align:middle line:90%
is equal to x/2, 3x over 2.

00:18:43.260 --> 00:18:49.460 align:middle line:90%


00:18:49.460 --> 00:18:57.585 align:middle line:84%
And since 0 is not in
this set, in this set,

00:18:57.585 --> 00:19:14.540 align:middle line:84%
[? implies ?] intersect S
take away x equals empty, OK?

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:18.620 align:middle line:84%
So we had to find a delta so
that this interval around x

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:21.230 align:middle line:84%
doesn't contain anything
from S, and we've done that

00:19:21.230 --> 00:19:22.820 align:middle line:90%
by choosing delta 0 to be x/2.

00:19:22.820 --> 00:19:31.630 align:middle line:90%


00:19:31.630 --> 00:19:32.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:36.500 align:middle line:90%


00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:39.830 align:middle line:84%
So I could have
done it for just--

00:19:39.830 --> 00:19:45.450 align:middle line:84%
so I did it for a set
containing just one element,

00:19:45.450 --> 00:19:48.360 align:middle line:84%
showed that this set
has no cluster points.

00:19:48.360 --> 00:19:52.050 align:middle line:84%
You can also show that if
it has finitely many points,

00:19:52.050 --> 00:19:55.560 align:middle line:90%
it has no cluster points.

00:19:55.560 --> 00:20:00.200 align:middle line:84%
And so therefore, any finite
set has no cluster points,

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:03.220 align:middle line:84%
but being a cluster
point has nothing

00:20:03.220 --> 00:20:04.420 align:middle line:90%
to do with the cardinality.

00:20:04.420 --> 00:20:07.120 align:middle line:84%
So if you see the example
in the notes, which

00:20:07.120 --> 00:20:09.710 align:middle line:84%
you can think about, and I'm
not going to go over right here,

00:20:09.710 --> 00:20:14.650 align:middle line:84%
but, for example, x equals
z, the set of integers--

00:20:14.650 --> 00:20:23.990 align:middle line:90%


00:20:23.990 --> 00:20:30.120 align:middle line:90%
this has no cluster points, OK?

00:20:30.120 --> 00:20:35.890 align:middle line:84%
So being a cluster point means,
where is this set clustering?

00:20:35.890 --> 00:20:38.490 align:middle line:84%
So it has nothing necessarily
to do with the size of the set

00:20:38.490 --> 00:20:45.980 align:middle line:84%
but where the set is taking up
space in the real number line.

00:20:45.980 --> 00:20:55.990 align:middle line:84%
All right, so with the
definition of cluster points,

00:20:55.990 --> 00:20:59.020 align:middle line:84%
let me first state the
theorem that, in fact, you

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:08.355 align:middle line:84%
proved in the assignment, which
is that for cluster points--

00:21:08.355 --> 00:21:11.100 align:middle line:90%


00:21:11.100 --> 00:21:22.810 align:middle line:84%
let S be a subset of R, and
x is a cluster point of S

00:21:22.810 --> 00:21:30.880 align:middle line:84%
if and only if
there exist sequence

00:21:30.880 --> 00:21:43.600 align:middle line:84%
xn of the elements of and S take
away x such that xn converges

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:46.288 align:middle line:90%
to x, OK?

00:21:46.288 --> 00:21:47.580 align:middle line:90%
And that was in the assignment.

00:21:47.580 --> 00:21:50.490 align:middle line:84%
You proved that basically
using the squeeze theorem

00:21:50.490 --> 00:21:53.720 align:middle line:90%
in the definition.

00:21:53.720 --> 00:21:56.660 align:middle line:84%
All right, so with the
notion of a cluster point,

00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:59.360 align:middle line:84%
these are the points
in a set where

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:02.420 align:middle line:84%
we're going to start talking
about how a function behaves

00:22:02.420 --> 00:22:09.700 align:middle line:84%
near a point, which is the
notion of a limit of a function

00:22:09.700 --> 00:22:11.550 align:middle line:90%
is our next definition.

00:22:11.550 --> 00:22:14.232 align:middle line:90%


00:22:14.232 --> 00:22:19.400 align:middle line:84%
Let S be a subset of R. And
even though I was referring

00:22:19.400 --> 00:22:21.320 align:middle line:84%
to cluster points
earlier as x, we're

00:22:21.320 --> 00:22:24.830 align:middle line:90%
now going to switch over to c.

00:22:24.830 --> 00:22:38.050 align:middle line:84%
Let c be cluster point of S.
And let f be a function from S

00:22:38.050 --> 00:22:41.900 align:middle line:90%
to R, all right?

00:22:41.900 --> 00:22:55.880 align:middle line:84%
So you say f of x converges
to L as x goes to c.

00:22:55.880 --> 00:23:00.890 align:middle line:84%
So this is the new
terminology here.

00:23:00.890 --> 00:23:05.700 align:middle line:90%


00:23:05.700 --> 00:23:10.100 align:middle line:84%
So here, L is a real number
if, for every epsilon positive,

00:23:10.100 --> 00:23:22.485 align:middle line:84%
there exists delta positive
such that if x is in S,

00:23:22.485 --> 00:23:27.360 align:middle line:84%
the absolute value of x
minus c is bigger than 0 less

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:34.170 align:middle line:84%
than delta, then f of x
minus L is less than epsilon.

00:23:34.170 --> 00:23:41.680 align:middle line:84%
So let's try and compare
this definition a little bit

00:23:41.680 --> 00:23:43.910 align:middle line:90%
to what happens for a sequence.

00:23:43.910 --> 00:23:49.270 align:middle line:84%
So for a sequence, the
sequence is getting close to L

00:23:49.270 --> 00:23:52.390 align:middle line:84%
as long as we go far
enough out in the sequence,

00:23:52.390 --> 00:23:54.820 align:middle line:84%
as long as we look at
terms far enough out.

00:23:54.820 --> 00:23:58.540 align:middle line:84%
Now, for limits of functions,
that going far enough

00:23:58.540 --> 00:24:01.030 align:middle line:84%
out along the sequence
is replaced by,

00:24:01.030 --> 00:24:03.580 align:middle line:84%
as long as we look close
enough to the point c

00:24:03.580 --> 00:24:05.170 align:middle line:90%
but not at the point c.

00:24:05.170 --> 00:24:16.630 align:middle line:84%
So if you'd like, this
says that if x is near c--

00:24:16.630 --> 00:24:19.510 align:middle line:84%
and so this is just an
intuitive interpretation

00:24:19.510 --> 00:24:21.760 align:middle line:90%
of what this definition says.

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:32.360 align:middle line:84%
If x is near c, then f of x is
near L. And let me also throw

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:40.495 align:middle line:84%
in here that we're saying that
x is near c but not equal to c.

00:24:40.495 --> 00:24:45.230 align:middle line:84%
But for a limit, you don't
look at what happens at f of c.

00:24:45.230 --> 00:24:49.160 align:middle line:84%
The function doesn't even
need to be defined there to be

00:24:49.160 --> 00:24:50.750 align:middle line:90%
able to define what a limit is.

00:24:50.750 --> 00:24:54.260 align:middle line:84%
We just care about what
happens nearby, OK?

00:24:54.260 --> 00:24:58.640 align:middle line:90%
So you could have--

00:24:58.640 --> 00:25:02.000 align:middle line:84%
the picture you should have
in mind is that here's c,

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.930 align:middle line:84%
and maybe f is not even
defined up to there,

00:25:07.930 --> 00:25:11.455 align:middle line:84%
but there is f, the graph
of the function f there.

00:25:11.455 --> 00:25:17.340 align:middle line:90%


00:25:17.340 --> 00:25:25.470 align:middle line:84%
There's L, and as long
as I get very close to c,

00:25:25.470 --> 00:25:30.820 align:middle line:84%
I'll be very close
to L, "very close"

00:25:30.820 --> 00:25:40.243 align:middle line:84%
being measured within
some strip here, OK?

00:25:40.243 --> 00:25:45.720 align:middle line:90%


00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:52.440 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is the notion
of the limit of a function

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:56.310 align:middle line:84%
as we approach a cluster point
of the set S where the function

00:25:56.310 --> 00:25:58.740 align:middle line:90%
f is defined.

00:25:58.740 --> 00:26:00.330 align:middle line:90%
Just a little bit of notation--

00:26:00.330 --> 00:26:04.150 align:middle line:90%


00:26:04.150 --> 00:26:07.510 align:middle line:84%
typically write like
we did with sequences

00:26:07.510 --> 00:26:12.670 align:middle line:84%
f of x converges to L as f of
x arrow L. And then I'll write,

00:26:12.670 --> 00:26:14.380 align:middle line:90%
as x goes to c.

00:26:14.380 --> 00:26:17.480 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I won't write
as x goes to c.

00:26:17.480 --> 00:26:22.970 align:middle line:84%
We note this by limit of
f of x equals L as well.

00:26:22.970 --> 00:26:27.180 align:middle line:90%


00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:32.910 align:middle line:84%
OK, so first question about
limits is, are they unique?

00:26:32.910 --> 00:26:38.610 align:middle line:84%
And this is, in
fact, why we require

00:26:38.610 --> 00:26:43.050 align:middle line:84%
that c be a cluster point of
S because if we didn't require

00:26:43.050 --> 00:26:45.240 align:middle line:84%
c to be a cluster point
of S in this definition,

00:26:45.240 --> 00:26:46.587 align:middle line:90%
limits would not be unique.

00:26:46.587 --> 00:26:48.420 align:middle line:84%
In fact, you could have
functions converging

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:52.170 align:middle line:84%
to whatever you want because
the definition would then

00:26:52.170 --> 00:26:52.920 align:middle line:90%
be vacuous.

00:26:52.920 --> 00:26:57.400 align:middle line:84%
But if you don't want to
think about that, that's fine.

00:26:57.400 --> 00:26:58.300 align:middle line:90%
It's not a big issue.

00:26:58.300 --> 00:27:00.670 align:middle line:84%
But I'm just going to
point out at one point,

00:27:00.670 --> 00:27:03.060 align:middle line:84%
we're going to use the fact
that c is a cluster point

00:27:03.060 --> 00:27:05.770 align:middle line:90%
to prove the following theorem.

00:27:05.770 --> 00:27:26.240 align:middle line:84%
So let c be a cluster point
of S, which is a subset of R.

00:27:26.240 --> 00:27:30.652 align:middle line:84%
And let f be a
function from S to R.

00:27:30.652 --> 00:27:38.230 align:middle line:84%
If f of x converges
to L1 as x goes to c,

00:27:38.230 --> 00:27:48.630 align:middle line:84%
and f of x converges to L2 as
x goes to c, then L1 equals L2,

00:27:48.630 --> 00:27:49.130 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:27:49.130 --> 00:27:52.580 align:middle line:84%
So this is what I
mean by uniqueness,

00:27:52.580 --> 00:27:56.210 align:middle line:84%
that a function can only have
one limit as it approaches

00:27:56.210 --> 00:27:57.050 align:middle line:90%
a point c.

00:27:57.050 --> 00:27:59.940 align:middle line:90%


00:27:59.940 --> 00:28:02.816 align:middle line:90%
Let me give the proof.

00:28:02.816 --> 00:28:07.720 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
play this game again,

00:28:07.720 --> 00:28:10.485 align:middle line:84%
where instead of showing
something as 0 or something is

00:28:10.485 --> 00:28:11.860 align:middle line:84%
equal to something
else directly,

00:28:11.860 --> 00:28:15.300 align:middle line:84%
we'll give ourselves a little
room and prove the following.

00:28:15.300 --> 00:28:20.850 align:middle line:84%
We'll instead show that
while epsilon positive,

00:28:20.850 --> 00:28:24.310 align:middle line:84%
L1 minus L2 is
less than epsilon.

00:28:24.310 --> 00:28:29.040 align:middle line:84%
So L1 and L2, these are
just two fixed real numbers.

00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:30.990 align:middle line:84%
If their absolute value
is less than epsilon

00:28:30.990 --> 00:28:34.020 align:middle line:84%
for arbitrary
epsilon, then this is

00:28:34.020 --> 00:28:38.040 align:middle line:84%
a number which is smaller
than any positive real number.

00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:41.730 align:middle line:84%
That implies that that number
is 0, so L1 equals L2, OK?

00:28:41.730 --> 00:28:44.880 align:middle line:90%


00:28:44.880 --> 00:28:46.650 align:middle line:84%
Why we give ourselves
a little room

00:28:46.650 --> 00:28:49.920 align:middle line:84%
is because, in the definition,
we have a small parameter there

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:51.426 align:middle line:90%
which we hope to use.

00:28:51.426 --> 00:28:56.730 align:middle line:90%
So let's prove this.

00:28:56.730 --> 00:28:58.540 align:middle line:90%
Let epsilon be positive.

00:28:58.540 --> 00:29:01.720 align:middle line:90%


00:29:01.720 --> 00:29:10.890 align:middle line:84%
So since f of x converges
to L1, there exists--

00:29:10.890 --> 00:29:14.830 align:middle line:84%
so just from the definition,
given some small tolerance,

00:29:14.830 --> 00:29:23.410 align:middle line:84%
I can find a little
number delta so

00:29:23.410 --> 00:29:25.240 align:middle line:84%
that if I look
inside this interval,

00:29:25.240 --> 00:29:30.260 align:middle line:84%
I get mapped to the interval L
plus epsilon, L minus epsilon.

00:29:30.260 --> 00:29:36.450 align:middle line:84%
So there exists a
delta 1 positive

00:29:36.450 --> 00:29:43.253 align:middle line:84%
such that if x is in S-- and
I'm going to probably keep

00:29:43.253 --> 00:29:44.670 align:middle line:84%
forgetting to write
that, but that

00:29:44.670 --> 00:29:47.640 align:middle line:84%
should be understood that x is
in the domain of the function

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:48.600 align:middle line:90%
f.

00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:54.660 align:middle line:84%
If x minus c is less than
delta 1 and bigger than 0,

00:29:54.660 --> 00:30:07.950 align:middle line:84%
then f of x minus L1 is
less than epsilon/2, OK?

00:30:07.950 --> 00:30:10.500 align:middle line:90%
And the same thing for L2.

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:13.560 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if f of x
is converging to L2,

00:30:13.560 --> 00:30:17.560 align:middle line:84%
then there exists a delta 2 so
that I have the same statement.

00:30:17.560 --> 00:30:30.530 align:middle line:84%
So instead, I'm just going to
change this 1 to i, i, i, i.

00:30:30.530 --> 00:30:32.940 align:middle line:90%
And here, i equals 1 too.

00:30:32.940 --> 00:30:37.340 align:middle line:84%
So since f of x converges to
each of these two numbers, L1

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:40.430 align:middle line:84%
and L2, there exists
a delta 1 and a delta

00:30:40.430 --> 00:30:44.480 align:middle line:84%
2 so that if I'm within
this tolerance delta of 1

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:47.840 align:middle line:84%
or delta 2, then f
of x minus delta 1--

00:30:47.840 --> 00:30:50.270 align:middle line:90%
L1 or L2 is less than epsilon/2.

00:30:50.270 --> 00:30:55.030 align:middle line:90%


00:30:55.030 --> 00:30:57.985 align:middle line:84%
Let delta be the minimum
of these two numbers.

00:30:57.985 --> 00:31:03.010 align:middle line:90%


00:31:03.010 --> 00:31:13.390 align:middle line:84%
Now, since c is a cluster
point of S, in fact,

00:31:13.390 --> 00:31:21.130 align:middle line:84%
there does exist an x in
S such that 0 is bigger

00:31:21.130 --> 00:31:26.330 align:middle line:84%
than x minus c is less
than delta, all right?

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:29.015 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to use this
x to compare L1 and L2.

00:31:29.015 --> 00:31:31.880 align:middle line:90%


00:31:31.880 --> 00:31:37.810 align:middle line:84%
Then since x is in this
interval, or I should say,

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:38.560 align:middle line:90%
since it's--

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:41.969 align:middle line:90%


00:31:41.969 --> 00:31:45.090 align:middle line:84%
so remember I had
this, which means

00:31:45.090 --> 00:31:51.910 align:middle line:84%
I have this inequality
or i equals 1, 2.

00:31:51.910 --> 00:31:58.540 align:middle line:84%
I get f of x, or I
should say, L1 minus L2.

00:31:58.540 --> 00:32:10.510 align:middle line:84%
This is equal to if I
add and subtract f of x

00:32:10.510 --> 00:32:19.370 align:middle line:84%
and now use the
triangle inequality

00:32:19.370 --> 00:32:23.870 align:middle line:84%
and use the inequality that's
in green, the f of x minus L1

00:32:23.870 --> 00:32:26.330 align:middle line:90%
is less than epsilon/2.

00:32:26.330 --> 00:32:28.220 align:middle line:90%
And same for L2, I get--

00:32:28.220 --> 00:32:33.110 align:middle line:90%


00:32:33.110 --> 00:32:34.770 align:middle line:90%
equals epsilon, OK?

00:32:34.770 --> 00:32:36.680 align:middle line:84%
And that's the end
because remember

00:32:36.680 --> 00:32:42.995 align:middle line:84%
we started off with the
absolute value of L1 minus L2.

00:32:42.995 --> 00:32:44.555 align:middle line:84%
Are there any
questions about that?

00:32:44.555 --> 00:32:58.642 align:middle line:90%


00:32:58.642 --> 00:33:04.420 align:middle line:84%
OK, so not the most
exciting theorem

00:33:04.420 --> 00:33:08.530 align:middle line:84%
in the world that this
thing that we've defined.

00:33:08.530 --> 00:33:16.010 align:middle line:84%
A limit is a unique
thing for function.

00:33:16.010 --> 00:33:18.055 align:middle line:84%
But let's start looking
at some examples.

00:33:18.055 --> 00:33:25.160 align:middle line:90%


00:33:25.160 --> 00:33:27.350 align:middle line:84%
And at one point, we'll
look at the negation

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:29.250 align:middle line:90%
of this definition.

00:33:29.250 --> 00:33:33.890 align:middle line:84%
