No questions?

00:48:57.480 --> 00:49:11.140 align:middle line:90%


00:49:11.140 --> 00:49:16.120 align:middle line:84%
All right, so what we'll
talk about now is--

00:49:16.120 --> 00:49:22.090 align:middle line:84%
so before this section
on continuous functions,

00:49:22.090 --> 00:49:24.490 align:middle line:84%
or at least this section
on limits of functions,

00:49:24.490 --> 00:49:29.130 align:middle line:84%
we had the notion of
limits of sequences.

00:49:29.130 --> 00:49:31.110 align:middle line:84%
And so a natural
question is, how

00:49:31.110 --> 00:49:37.320 align:middle line:84%
do limits of functions
and limits of sequences

00:49:37.320 --> 00:49:41.340 align:middle line:84%
belong together, interact,
relate to each other, I guess,

00:49:41.340 --> 00:49:43.890 align:middle line:84%
is the best way to
phrase that question.

00:49:43.890 --> 00:49:46.560 align:middle line:90%


00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:51.480 align:middle line:84%
And the point is that to
decide if a function has

00:49:51.480 --> 00:49:56.310 align:middle line:84%
a limit it, suffices to stick in
sequences that converge to that

00:49:56.310 --> 00:49:58.450 align:middle line:90%
point that you're looking at.

00:49:58.450 --> 00:50:00.840 align:middle line:84%
And that's the content
of the next theorem.

00:50:00.840 --> 00:50:20.950 align:middle line:84%
So let S be a subset of
R, c cluster point of S.

00:50:20.950 --> 00:50:24.990 align:middle line:90%
Let f be a function from S to R.

00:50:24.990 --> 00:50:33.180 align:middle line:90%
Then the limit exists.

00:50:33.180 --> 00:50:39.270 align:middle line:84%
Limit as x goes to c of f of
x equals a number L. This is

00:50:39.270 --> 00:50:46.110 align:middle line:84%
equivalent to the statement
that for every sequence

00:50:46.110 --> 00:50:51.440 align:middle line:84%
x sub n of elements
of S take away

00:50:51.440 --> 00:51:08.160 align:middle line:84%
c such that xn converges to c,
we have f of xn converges to L,

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:08.730 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:51:08.730 --> 00:51:10.355 align:middle line:84%
So again, the statement
of this theorem

00:51:10.355 --> 00:51:14.850 align:middle line:84%
is that a function
converges to L if and only

00:51:14.850 --> 00:51:18.000 align:middle line:84%
if for every sequence I
stick into the function which

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:23.540 align:middle line:84%
converges to c, f of x
then converges to L. So

00:51:23.540 --> 00:51:27.980 align:middle line:84%
to choose or to decide
if a function converges,

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:31.220 align:middle line:84%
it suffices to
look at convergence

00:51:31.220 --> 00:51:32.810 align:middle line:90%
of certain sequences, OK?

00:51:32.810 --> 00:51:37.890 align:middle line:90%


00:51:37.890 --> 00:51:38.390 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:38.390 --> 00:51:41.130 align:middle line:90%


00:51:41.130 --> 00:51:44.260 align:middle line:84%
And why is this
theorem important,

00:51:44.260 --> 00:51:45.520 align:middle line:90%
or at least very useful?

00:51:45.520 --> 00:51:51.540 align:middle line:84%
It's because with this
theorem, we now get basically

00:51:51.540 --> 00:51:55.620 align:middle line:84%
every analog of theorems we
proved for sequences for free,

00:51:55.620 --> 00:52:01.020 align:middle line:84%
for example, limits of sums
of functions, a squeeze

00:52:01.020 --> 00:52:08.600 align:middle line:84%
theorem that can be stated for
limits of functions, and so on.

00:52:08.600 --> 00:52:10.300 align:middle line:84%
And I'll say a few
comments about this

00:52:10.300 --> 00:52:11.500 align:middle line:90%
after we proved the theorem.

00:52:11.500 --> 00:52:16.050 align:middle line:90%


00:52:16.050 --> 00:52:17.420 align:middle line:90%
All right, so let's--

00:52:17.420 --> 00:52:18.610 align:middle line:90%
this is a two-way street.

00:52:18.610 --> 00:52:22.060 align:middle line:90%


00:52:22.060 --> 00:52:28.310 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to mark the
second statement in green.

00:52:28.310 --> 00:52:30.810 align:middle line:84%
That way, I don't have
to rewrite it again.

00:52:30.810 --> 00:52:38.460 align:middle line:84%
So first, assume that limit at
x goes to c of f of x equals L,

00:52:38.460 --> 00:52:44.356 align:middle line:84%
and now we want to prove
the statement in green, OK?

00:52:44.356 --> 00:52:48.310 align:middle line:90%
So here's the idea.

00:52:48.310 --> 00:52:49.620 align:middle line:90%
So now we want to show--

00:52:49.620 --> 00:53:02.180 align:middle line:84%
so let xn be a sequence
of elements in S

00:53:02.180 --> 00:53:09.550 align:middle line:84%
take away c such that
x sub n converges to c.

00:53:09.550 --> 00:53:14.490 align:middle line:84%
And what we want
to show is that f

00:53:14.490 --> 00:53:20.070 align:middle line:84%
of xn, which is
now a new sequence

00:53:20.070 --> 00:53:23.890 align:middle line:84%
converges to L as
n goes to infinity.

00:53:23.890 --> 00:53:27.520 align:middle line:90%


00:53:27.520 --> 00:53:31.050 align:middle line:84%
OK, so here, you
should write, as n

00:53:31.050 --> 00:53:40.205 align:middle line:90%
goes to infinity, in here, OK?

00:53:40.205 --> 00:53:45.440 align:middle line:84%
So let me move that, and let
me draw the picture of why

00:53:45.440 --> 00:53:46.460 align:middle line:90%
you should believe this.

00:53:46.460 --> 00:53:49.380 align:middle line:90%


00:53:49.380 --> 00:53:51.620 align:middle line:84%
So remember, what it
means for a sequence

00:53:51.620 --> 00:53:54.750 align:middle line:84%
to converge to a number
means, for every epsilon,

00:53:54.750 --> 00:53:57.470 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital M
so that for all n bigger

00:53:57.470 --> 00:54:01.130 align:middle line:84%
than or equal to capital M, the
sequence is close to the number

00:54:01.130 --> 00:54:03.170 align:middle line:90%
L within epsilon distance to it.

00:54:03.170 --> 00:54:08.760 align:middle line:84%
So let's think about
this a little bit.

00:54:08.760 --> 00:54:10.520 align:middle line:90%
I'm not going to draw the graph.

00:54:10.520 --> 00:54:15.990 align:middle line:84%
I'm just going to draw two
copies of the number line.

00:54:15.990 --> 00:54:22.100 align:middle line:84%
Here, we have the
number L. Here's

00:54:22.100 --> 00:54:29.350 align:middle line:84%
the number c and L plus
epsilon, L minus epsilon.

00:54:29.350 --> 00:54:32.730 align:middle line:90%
So let epsilon be positive.

00:54:32.730 --> 00:54:35.770 align:middle line:90%


00:54:35.770 --> 00:54:39.100 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is we want
to be able to find or say

00:54:39.100 --> 00:54:41.380 align:middle line:84%
there exists a natural
number capital M so

00:54:41.380 --> 00:54:45.070 align:middle line:84%
that n bigger than or equal
to capital M implies f of xn

00:54:45.070 --> 00:54:47.920 align:middle line:90%
is inside this interval here.

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:57.030 align:middle line:84%
Now, since f of x converges
to L as x converges to c,

00:54:57.030 --> 00:55:02.550 align:middle line:90%
there exists a delta so that--

00:55:02.550 --> 00:55:05.890 align:middle line:84%
so this is the picture
that goes along with it--

00:55:05.890 --> 00:55:14.030 align:middle line:84%
so that if I'm inside
this interval here,

00:55:14.030 --> 00:55:19.708 align:middle line:84%
then I get mapped into
this interval here.

00:55:19.708 --> 00:55:22.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is what I get
from the assumption.

00:55:22.500 --> 00:55:27.170 align:middle line:90%


00:55:27.170 --> 00:55:30.350 align:middle line:84%
So then how I should choose
the natural number capital

00:55:30.350 --> 00:55:35.631 align:middle line:84%
M is so that all
of the x sub n's

00:55:35.631 --> 00:55:40.220 align:middle line:84%
lie in this interval, c
minus delta, c plus delta.

00:55:40.220 --> 00:55:42.230 align:middle line:84%
And if I can arrange
that, which I can

00:55:42.230 --> 00:55:46.910 align:middle line:84%
because the x sub
n's converge to c,

00:55:46.910 --> 00:55:51.160 align:middle line:84%
then I will get that
these guys get mapped

00:55:51.160 --> 00:55:55.700 align:middle line:84%
into this interval, L plus
epsilon, L minus epsilon, OK?

00:55:55.700 --> 00:55:57.400 align:middle line:84%
And that's the whole
idea of the proof.

00:55:57.400 --> 00:55:58.870 align:middle line:84%
Now we just need
to write it down.

00:55:58.870 --> 00:56:06.990 align:middle line:90%


00:56:06.990 --> 00:56:14.270 align:middle line:84%
Since f of x converges to L,
exists a delta positive such

00:56:14.270 --> 00:56:27.260 align:middle line:84%
that if less than delta, then if
x minus L is less than epsilon.

00:56:27.260 --> 00:56:29.280 align:middle line:84%
That's what I drew
in yellow there.

00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:39.590 align:middle line:84%
Now, since the sequence
x sub n equals c,

00:56:39.590 --> 00:56:42.350 align:middle line:84%
this implies that there exists
some natural number M sub

00:56:42.350 --> 00:56:50.030 align:middle line:84%
0 such that little n bigger
than or equal to M sub 0--

00:56:50.030 --> 00:56:53.660 align:middle line:84%
since all of these x sub n's are
not equal to c, by assumption,

00:56:53.660 --> 00:56:57.380 align:middle line:84%
they're in the
set S take away c.

00:56:57.380 --> 00:57:00.140 align:middle line:84%
X sub n minus c, and absolute
value is bigger than 0

00:57:00.140 --> 00:57:04.760 align:middle line:90%
and less than delta, OK?

00:57:04.760 --> 00:57:08.810 align:middle line:84%
This follows from the definition
of convergence of sequences

00:57:08.810 --> 00:57:09.380 align:middle line:90%
to a point.

00:57:09.380 --> 00:57:11.240 align:middle line:84%
Here, if you like,
I'm choosing epsilon

00:57:11.240 --> 00:57:13.460 align:middle line:90%
in that definition to be delta.

00:57:13.460 --> 00:57:16.820 align:middle line:84%
And this delta is coming
from the definition

00:57:16.820 --> 00:57:18.650 align:middle line:90%
for convergence of functions.

00:57:18.650 --> 00:57:23.420 align:middle line:90%


00:57:23.420 --> 00:57:29.365 align:middle line:84%
And so we'll choose capital
M to be this integer M sub 0.

00:57:29.365 --> 00:57:32.290 align:middle line:90%


00:57:32.290 --> 00:57:35.880 align:middle line:84%
And if n is bigger
than or equal to M,

00:57:35.880 --> 00:57:39.780 align:middle line:84%
I get that, by our choice
of it being M sub 0,

00:57:39.780 --> 00:57:43.320 align:middle line:84%
you get that x sub n minus
c is less than delta.

00:57:43.320 --> 00:57:46.350 align:middle line:84%
That means that it falls in
this little yellow highlighted

00:57:46.350 --> 00:57:53.170 align:middle line:84%
part in the first number
line, which implies--

00:57:53.170 --> 00:57:58.390 align:middle line:90%


00:57:58.390 --> 00:58:05.070 align:middle line:84%
so here, what I'm using is
what's highlighted in blue.

00:58:05.070 --> 00:58:10.850 align:middle line:84%
So this is content
of this implication--

00:58:10.850 --> 00:58:19.050 align:middle line:84%
implies that f of xn minus L is
less than epsilon, all right?

00:58:19.050 --> 00:58:20.860 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we
wanted to do, right?

00:58:20.860 --> 00:58:23.940 align:middle line:84%
We wanted to show that there
exists some natural number

00:58:23.940 --> 00:58:28.260 align:middle line:84%
M so that n bigger than or equal
to M implies f of x minus L

00:58:28.260 --> 00:58:31.070 align:middle line:84%
is less than epsilon
in absolute value.

00:58:31.070 --> 00:58:37.630 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, we've
proved that the limit as n

00:58:37.630 --> 00:58:48.365 align:middle line:84%
goes to infinity of the
sequence f of xn equals L.

00:58:48.365 --> 00:58:51.610 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's one direction of
this if-and-only-if statement.

00:58:51.610 --> 00:58:54.710 align:middle line:84%
Let's prove the
opposite direction.

00:58:54.710 --> 00:59:00.155 align:middle line:84%
So suppose what's
highlighted in green holds.

00:59:00.155 --> 00:59:06.991 align:middle line:90%


00:59:06.991 --> 00:59:07.990 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:59:07.990 --> 00:59:10.700 align:middle line:84%
And this proof is going
to be by contradiction.

00:59:10.700 --> 00:59:15.430 align:middle line:84%
So let's suppose that our
assumption, what's in green,

00:59:15.430 --> 00:59:16.090 align:middle line:90%
holds.

00:59:16.090 --> 00:59:20.761 align:middle line:84%
But the limit as x goes to c
of f of x does not equal L.

00:59:20.761 --> 00:59:27.740 align:middle line:84%
And now we're going to do
the proof by contradiction,

00:59:27.740 --> 00:59:29.825 align:middle line:84%
meaning suppose the
outcome is false.

00:59:29.825 --> 00:59:37.490 align:middle line:90%


00:59:37.490 --> 00:59:38.950 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:59:38.950 --> 00:59:40.780 align:middle line:84%
We're still assuming
what's in green holds.

00:59:40.780 --> 00:59:41.930 align:middle line:90%
That's our assumption.

00:59:41.930 --> 00:59:44.590 align:middle line:84%
And for proof by
contradiction, we

00:59:44.590 --> 00:59:48.520 align:middle line:84%
assume that the outcome
or the conclusion

00:59:48.520 --> 00:59:51.790 align:middle line:84%
is false, which is that the
limit as x goes to c of f of x

00:59:51.790 --> 00:59:55.120 align:middle line:90%
does not equal L.

00:59:55.120 --> 00:59:57.260 align:middle line:90%
Now, what does this mean?

00:59:57.260 --> 00:59:59.080 align:middle line:84%
So now we get to
negate the definition

00:59:59.080 --> 01:00:04.870 align:middle line:84%
and get better
acquainted with it.

01:00:04.870 --> 01:00:09.030 align:middle line:84%
This means that--
so the definition

01:00:09.030 --> 01:00:13.750 align:middle line:84%
of limit, if you go back to
the notes is, for all epsilon,

01:00:13.750 --> 01:00:17.160 align:middle line:90%
there exists a delta statement.

01:00:17.160 --> 01:00:20.060 align:middle line:84%
So the negation is
that there exists

01:00:20.060 --> 01:00:24.900 align:middle line:84%
some bad epsilon,
epsilon 0, such

01:00:24.900 --> 01:00:33.610 align:middle line:84%
that for all delta positive,
there exists an x such

01:00:33.610 --> 01:00:50.300 align:middle line:84%
that x is close to c, but f
of x is far away from L. OK?

01:00:50.300 --> 01:00:51.680 align:middle line:84%
So the negation
of the definition

01:00:51.680 --> 01:00:53.600 align:middle line:84%
of limit of something
being the limit

01:00:53.600 --> 01:00:56.220 align:middle line:84%
is that there
exists a bad epsilon

01:00:56.220 --> 01:01:00.110 align:middle line:84%
so that no matter
how close I get to c,

01:01:00.110 --> 01:01:03.800 align:middle line:84%
I can find something very close
to c that's far away from L

01:01:03.800 --> 01:01:07.630 align:middle line:90%
if I stick it into f, OK?

01:01:07.630 --> 01:01:12.660 align:middle line:84%
That's the intuitive way
of viewing the negation

01:01:12.660 --> 01:01:13.680 align:middle line:90%
of this definition.

01:01:13.680 --> 01:01:17.070 align:middle line:90%


01:01:17.070 --> 01:01:19.860 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now I'm
going to apply this

01:01:19.860 --> 01:01:25.830 align:middle line:84%
with delta chosen to be 1/n
for in a natural number, OK?

01:01:25.830 --> 01:01:29.670 align:middle line:90%


01:01:29.670 --> 01:01:35.800 align:middle line:84%
And this says-- so
this statement here

01:01:35.800 --> 01:01:37.700 align:middle line:90%
is a for-all-delta statement.

01:01:37.700 --> 01:01:42.640 align:middle line:84%
So that holds for
every delta I pick.

01:01:42.640 --> 01:01:52.020 align:middle line:84%
So for all n, a natural number,
there exists an x sub n such

01:01:52.020 --> 01:01:56.962 align:middle line:84%
that 0 is bigger than x sub n
minus c is less than delta--

01:01:56.962 --> 01:01:58.170 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to pick to be 1/n--

01:01:58.170 --> 01:02:08.100 align:middle line:90%


01:02:08.100 --> 01:02:11.310 align:middle line:84%
and f of x sub n minus L
is bigger than or equal

01:02:11.310 --> 01:02:12.300 align:middle line:90%
to epsilon 0.

01:02:12.300 --> 01:02:15.630 align:middle line:84%
So first off, I made
a for-all-n statement.

01:02:15.630 --> 01:02:17.710 align:middle line:84%
Let's think about this
for just a second.

01:02:17.710 --> 01:02:19.410 align:middle line:84%
So certainly, for
delta equals 1,

01:02:19.410 --> 01:02:24.270 align:middle line:84%
I can find a number x sub 1
satisfying 0 is less than x

01:02:24.270 --> 01:02:28.740 align:middle line:84%
minus c is less than 1, and f
of x minus f of x sub 1 minus

01:02:28.740 --> 01:02:32.010 align:middle line:84%
L is bigger than or
equal to epsilon 0.

01:02:32.010 --> 01:02:36.300 align:middle line:84%
But delta can be anything I
choose, so for delta equal 1/2,

01:02:36.300 --> 01:02:38.940 align:middle line:84%
I can find an x
sub 2 such that x

01:02:38.940 --> 01:02:43.890 align:middle line:84%
sub 2 minus c is less than
1/2, and f of x minus L

01:02:43.890 --> 01:02:45.840 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than or
equal to epsilon 0.

01:02:45.840 --> 01:02:51.047 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just choosing delta
to be 1/n for each n,

01:02:51.047 --> 01:02:51.755 align:middle line:90%
a natural number.

01:02:51.755 --> 01:02:57.340 align:middle line:90%


01:02:57.340 --> 01:03:04.002 align:middle line:90%
Choosing delta to be 1/n, OK?

01:03:04.002 --> 01:03:04.835 align:middle line:90%
Is this point clear?

01:03:04.835 --> 01:03:11.530 align:middle line:90%


01:03:11.530 --> 01:03:15.430 align:middle line:84%
OK, please stop me if you
have questions and something

01:03:15.430 --> 01:03:17.620 align:middle line:90%
is not clear.

01:03:17.620 --> 01:03:22.950 align:middle line:84%
OK, so I have this
sequence of elements of S

01:03:22.950 --> 01:03:24.750 align:middle line:84%
that are not equal
to c because they

01:03:24.750 --> 01:03:28.170 align:middle line:84%
are an absolute
value bigger than 0,

01:03:28.170 --> 01:03:32.610 align:middle line:84%
or the absolute value of x sub
n minus c is bigger than 0.

01:03:32.610 --> 01:03:36.690 align:middle line:84%
And they satisfy these
two inequalities, OK?

01:03:36.690 --> 01:03:41.500 align:middle line:90%


01:03:41.500 --> 01:03:44.035 align:middle line:84%
Then let me just write
this inequality again.

01:03:44.035 --> 01:03:50.430 align:middle line:90%


01:03:50.430 --> 01:03:54.390 align:middle line:84%
So then the inequality
that I have is, for all n,

01:03:54.390 --> 01:03:57.210 align:middle line:84%
the natural number 0 is
less than x sub n minus c

01:03:57.210 --> 01:03:59.460 align:middle line:90%
is less than 1/n.

01:03:59.460 --> 01:04:02.760 align:middle line:84%
I claim that the x sub n's
must then converge to c.

01:04:02.760 --> 01:04:06.870 align:middle line:90%
What tool can I use to say that?

01:04:06.870 --> 01:04:14.570 align:middle line:90%


01:04:14.570 --> 01:04:17.730 align:middle line:90%
Squeeze theorem, OK?

01:04:17.730 --> 01:04:20.190 align:middle line:84%
Because this thing
on the left, 0--

01:04:20.190 --> 01:04:22.770 align:middle line:84%
this, if you like,
is a sequence, just

01:04:22.770 --> 01:04:23.670 align:middle line:90%
a constant sequence.

01:04:23.670 --> 01:04:25.470 align:middle line:90%
This converges to 0.

01:04:25.470 --> 01:04:29.100 align:middle line:84%
And 1/n, something on
the right, converges to 0

01:04:29.100 --> 01:04:30.280 align:middle line:90%
as n goes to infinity.

01:04:30.280 --> 01:04:32.280 align:middle line:84%
So that implies the
thing that's sandwiched

01:04:32.280 --> 01:04:34.470 align:middle line:90%
in between gets squeezed to 0.

01:04:34.470 --> 01:04:40.640 align:middle line:84%
So that implies limit as n goes
to infinity of x sub n minus c

01:04:40.640 --> 01:04:45.860 align:middle line:84%
equals 0, i.e.,
xn's converge to c.

01:04:45.860 --> 01:04:50.150 align:middle line:84%
Now, I'm assuming what's
in green holds, which

01:04:50.150 --> 01:04:54.170 align:middle line:84%
is, if I take any sequence
converging to c, f of xn

